<i><b>The Fury of Tunare</i></b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/urelbeekeinre.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Relbeek Einre</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>uncommonly Good</span><br>  Posts: 1759<br> <font color=#CC9900>(2/27/01 11:18:59 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.tigerden.com/~twilight/keebler-60x60.jpg BORDER=0></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Remember how you would like to be treated.</span><hr size=1> Well Thorondar, that leads to another question.<br>
<br>
How long between attempts at a named FCFS mob should a group be allotted before another group moves in? Certainly if a group is taking six hours to regroup that's unreasonable for them to 'claim' said mob for that amount of time. And certainly a half hour is reasonable. Where's the cutoff? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/udauros.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dauros</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 52<br> <font color=#CC9900>(2/27/01 11:44:01 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Remember how you would like to be treated.</span><hr size=1> One way to look at it is the mob spawn time *shrug* but that's sometimes not a good way to look at things.<br>
<br>
If we introduce more rules into the system of FCFS, doesn't it kind of defeat the purpose of FCFS itself?  Ultimately the more rules you make the less FCFS it becomes....again, I think it all boils down to common courtesy. <p>Dauros 54th Enchanter of Ethos<BR>
Taeolin Retired Druid of Brell</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukruuunch.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kruuunch</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Ugliest Paladin o' Kaladim</span><br>  Posts: 1578<br> <font color=#CC9900>(2/27/01 12:40:44 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.krunch.net/kruunch-face.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Remember how you would like to be treated.</span><hr size=1> How about calling it ZoneInAndShowSomeFuckingRespect (ZIASSFR).<br>
<br>
In other words, basic courtesy. You zone into Ice Clad to do Lodizel and see a couple groups buffing for it. You wish them luck and go on to the next thing.<br>
<br>
You zone into COM and ask in OOC &quot;Are the lords taken?&quot; and wait for a reply and go from there.<br>
<br>
You zone into Kedge to see if the names are up. You ask in OOC if anyone in zone is planning on doing them. You receive no reply and bring your group in to do them. 30 minutes later someone pipes up and says &quot;HEY! We were planning on doing them!&quot;. You explain that you asked if anyone was doing them, and are very sorry from crossing them up (then continue killing Phinny or whoever since you were there first).<br>
<br>
I can't believe this topic needs to be &quot;discussed&quot;. Didn't you all learn this in kindergarten with blocks?<br>
<br>
&lt;--- very frustrated at people's lack of being able to share and play well with others. <p><FONT face="arial" size="-1"><B>Kruunch Spiritslammer (Ugliest Paladin o' Kaladim)
<BR><A HREF="http://www.krunch.net/spiritslammer">Clan Spiritslammer</A></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uadunofbrell.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Adun of Brell</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Burn the Witch!</span><br>  Posts: 1291<br> <font color=#CC9900>(2/27/01 12:43:15 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.pangea.ca/~grinch/ladun.jpg width=67 height=150></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Remember how you would like to be treated.</span><hr size=1> Thorondar, it's all about perspective.  I don't feel that mobs &quot;belong&quot; to anyone.  Say I'm in Cobalt Scar, &amp; I discover K'Dar is up.  Nobody else is in zone, and he just popped.  I'm the only person to know.  I start recruiting to kill him, &amp; 5 mins later, there are 6 DG people in zone.<br>
<br>
Someone from SR ports in, &amp; notices he's up.  SR starts getting people together.  Thirty mins later, DG is still just 6 people.  We have another 12 on the way, but they'll be another 30 mins or so.  SR is there in force, &amp; is ready to take the dragon.<br>
<br>
If we're unable to take the dragon, &amp; SR is, why can't they give it a shot?  It's rude of me to demand that SR leave, simply because I was there first.  SR had the raid crew there first, they can give it a shot.  Let's say they try &amp; fail.  They're doing CR.  The rest of my crew arrives.  I feel perfectly justified in having my try now.  SR's on CR, they're not prepared to engage the dragon, but my group is.<br>
<br>
Mobs aren't owned by anyone.  If you have the people there to do it, go for it.  If someone else was there first, let them try.  If they're not prepared to try, then they weren't really there first.<br>
<br>
If two parties form up independently at the same time, then the first to engage (not kite) the mob are the ones that kill it.  If the first group fails, the second is free to try it. Competition is a good thing.  It doesn't have to be about right/wrong.  If I compete with someone &amp; lose, so be it.  I gave it my best shot, &amp; perhaps I'll be better prepared, or invite more people next time.<br>
<br>
It's not being rude, it's simply a different form of courtesy.  The courtesy states: &quot;It's not appropriate for me to claim something that I'm not prepared to do.  If you are there &amp; prepared to do it, you have that right.&quot;<br>
<br>
I find people sitting at a zone claim &quot;claiming&quot; a spawn to be very rude.  In recognizing that I don't own a spawn, that spawn cannot be stolen from me, it never belonged to me in the first place.<br>
<br>
I remember the night I got the Pawduster.  When my group entered Karnor's, someone was claiming hands.  He wasn't there, so we went in.  Two hours pass by...  The guy still didn't have his group together.<br>
<br>
IMO, nothing less than a full raid crew ready to engage can claim a spawn as theirs.  Don't claim it, just go do it.  If you kill the mob in question, it's obviously yours.  If you can't kill it, or aren't ready it, it's obviously not yours yet, now is it? <p><img src="http://www.pangea.ca/~grinch/sadune2.jpg" width="400" height="175"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ugaramebonhands.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Garam Ebonhands</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Protector of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 302<br> <font color=#CC9900>(2/27/01 1:01:06 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Remember how you would like to be treated.</span><hr size=1> These aren't rules that are being introducing, they are guildlines.  This is an attempt to get a feeling of what everyone or what &quot;Brell Society&quot; thinks is FCFS.  There isn't going to be a vote because there is nothing to vote on. <br>
<br>
In Darkguard we were going to kill Phinny.  We got 6 people headed that way, checked the intentions board (RIP) and found another group was going to do it.  I was first to arrive at Unrest, saw that they had 3-4 people already there so we made the decision to go somewhere else and kill something else.  Yes, we could have mobilized before them, invis'd in and killed Phinny, but why?  We can always go back and kill him another time.  FCFS involves a little bit of respect and a lot of flexiblity.  It's just as easy to move onto something else and come back another time.<br>
<br>
The other thing with FCFS is that it's not about beating the system.  If in the above example if we invis'd in and surgically struck Phinny, we would have technically been in the right.  However, we knew they were there to do Phinny, we could have asked to join forces, but instead we just moved on.  The key to this is:  We didn't think we &quot;owned&quot; the mob.  So it was no skin off our back to go do something else.  &quot;We didn't get him this time, well we will get him next time&quot;.<br>
<br>
A lot of people talk about the time it took to get raiders together and buff up.  They think that this investment deserves the return of killing the phat lewt monster.  However, when they find that they can't for whatever reason kill that particular mob they generally just quit and go their seperate ways.  The fault here lies with the raid organizer.  You have 12-24 people itching to kill something, having invested an hour at the least, find something else for them to do.  Adune had planned a sky raid, when certain personnel failed to show, he tossed out alternatives.  So instead, we all went to Chardok, had an awesome raid and killed the king.  Instead, of 24 people losing 2 hours each, 19 people went to Chardok and had a kick ass time.<br>
<br>
<br>
Garam Ebonhands<br>
Army of One<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uaraldil000.showPublicProfile?language=EN>a raldil 000</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 31<br> <font color=#CC9900>(2/27/01 1:07:16 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Remember how you would like to be treated.</span><hr size=1>  As i see it the Party that has a sufficient force at the time to engage a mob has the right to it.<br>
 My reasoning is simple, it clears out many of the grey areas reguarding times, claims,and repeat attempts.<br>
 It is the way the game was designed right down to the moss snakes.<br>
   We have a reputation of being civil on Brell in an uncivil environment,thats quite a statement considering the nature of the game is survival of the fittest.<br>
  Have i been dumped on by another group? yes<br>
  I have also moved on, theres plenty to kill out there now.<br>
  Do i want to have to check the board for any move i make?<br>
 No. Do i think i can and do respect others? yes.to a fault<br>
